Topic 1: Client Interaction (Browser → Server Journey)
1. Concept Overview
Definition

Client Interaction is the complete process of how a user's request travels from their device (browser/mobile app) to a server and how the response comes back.

In simple words:

Everything that happens after you type a URL or click a button until you see the webpage.

Example:

You type:

www.amazon.com

↓

Browser contacts DNS

↓

Gets IP Address

↓

Request reaches Load Balancer

↓

Load Balancer picks a Server

↓

Server checks Cache

↓

If needed queries Database

↓

Response comes back

↓

Browser renders page
Why does it exist?

A browser cannot directly "know"

where the server is
which server to contact
where the data lives
how to receive the response

Many systems work together.

