5. Advantages
Separation of Responsibilities

Each component has one job.

Example:

DNS only resolves names.

Load Balancer only distributes traffic.

This modularity makes systems easier to scale and maintain.

Scalability

You can add more servers behind the load balancer as traffic grows.

Security

HTTPS encrypts data between client and server, protecting passwords and personal information.

Reliability

If one server fails, the load balancer can send traffic to another healthy server.

6. Disadvantages
Network Latency

Every hop adds delay.

Browser
↓

DNS
↓

Load Balancer
↓

Server
↓

Database

More hops → More latency.

Single Points of Failure

Without redundancy, a failure in DNS, load balancer, or database can make the service unavailable.

Complexity

Modern systems include many layers, making debugging and operations more challenging.

7. Trade-offs
Approach	Pros	Cons	Use When
Direct Client → Server	Simple	Doesn't scale well	Small applications
Client → Load Balancer → Servers	Scalable, fault tolerant	Extra infrastructure	Medium/Large systems
CDN → Load Balancer → Servers	Faster for global users	Higher cost	Global applications
8. Real-world Examples
Google: Browser → Global DNS → Edge servers → Load balancers → Search services → Index databases.
Amazon: Browser → DNS → CDN → Load balancer → Product service → Cache → Database.
Netflix: App → CDN → API Gateway → Microservices → Databases.
Uber: App → API Gateway → Ride service → Location service → Databases.
LinkedIn: Browser → Load balancer → Feed service → Cache → Databases.
